<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-144-384  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 144 384.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 27 1989 v6 n12 p15(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>National Weather Service asks Congress for new net. (computerizedweather-forecasting network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Weather Service requests $1 billion in funds from theCongress to update its nationwide network of radars, weathersatellites and field offices to improve the accuracy and lead timeof weather forecasts.andP;  The Advanced Weather Interactive ProcessingSystem (AWIPS) will expand forecasting lead time from four or fivedays to 10 days in advance.andP;  Tornado warnings will be able to beissued up to 30 minutes in advance compared to one to two minutesnow.andP;  AWIPS enhancements will include 160 Doppler radars, newsatellites, Class VII supercomputers and 1,000 microcomputer-basedweather sensors called automated surface observing systems (ASOS)that control 12 weather-sensing instruments.andP;  Currently, suchreadings must be made by hand, whereas ASOS will automaticallytake these readings every 10 minutes.andP;  The sensors will even allow250 forecast offices to be consolidates into 115.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Weather ServiceGovernment AgencyNetworksMeteorologyForecastingUpdatingRadar SystemsSensorsSatellites.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>